When Ed Thatcher climbed the marble steps of the wide hospital entry he\
was trembling. The smell of drugs caught at his throat. A woman with a\
starched face was looking at him over the top of a desk. He tried to\
steady his voice.\
\
\'93Can you tell me how Mrs. Thatcher is?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, you can go up.\'94\
\
\'93But please, miss, is everything all right?\'94\
\
\'93The nurse on the floor will know anything about the case. Stairs to\
the left, third floor, maternity ward.\'94\
\
Ed Thatcher held a bunch of flowers wrapped in green waxed paper. The\
broad stairs swayed as he stumbled up, his toes kicking against the\
brass rods that held the fiber matting down. The closing of a door cut\
off a strangled shriek. He stopped a nurse.\
\
\'93I want to see Mrs. Thatcher, please.\'94\
\
\'93Go right ahead if you know where she is.\'94\
\
\'93But they\'92ve moved her.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll have to ask at the desk at the end of the hall.\'94\
\
He gnawed his cold lips. At the end of the hall a redfaced woman looked\
at him, smiling.\
\
\'93Everything\'92s fine. You\'92re the happy father of a bouncing baby girl.\'94\
\
\'93You see it\'92s our first and Susie\'92s so delicate,\'94 he stammered with\
blinking eyes.\
\
\'93Oh yes, I understand, naturally you worried.... You can go in and talk\
to her when she wakes up. The baby was born two hours ago. Be sure not\
to tire her.\'94\
\
Ed Thatcher was a little man with two blond wisps of mustache and\
washedout gray eyes. He seized the nurse\'92s hand and shook it showing\
all his uneven yellow teeth in a smile.\
\
\'93You see it\'92s our first.\'94\
\
\'93Congratulations,\'94 said the nurse.\
\
Rows of beds under bilious gaslight, a sick smell of restlessly\
stirring bedclothes, faces fat, lean, yellow, white; that\'92s her.\
Susie\'92s yellow hair lay in a loose coil round her little white face\
that looked shriveled and twisted. He unwrapped the roses and put them\
on the night table. Looking out the window was like looking down into\
water. The trees in the square were tangled in blue cobwebs. Down the\
avenue lamps were coming on marking off with green shimmer brickpurple\
blocks of houses; chimney pots and water tanks cut sharp into a sky\
flushed like flesh. The blue lids slipped back off her eyes.\
\
\'93That you Ed?... Why Ed they are Jacks. How extravagant of you.\'94\
\
\'93I couldn\'92t help it dearest. I knew you liked them.\'94\
\
A nurse was hovering near the end of the bed.\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t you let us see the baby, miss?\'94\
\
The nurse nodded. She was a lanternjawed grayfaced woman with tight\
lips.\
\
\'93I hate her,\'94 whispered Susie. \'93She gives me the fidgets that woman\
does; she\'92s nothing but a mean old maid.\'94\
\
\'93Never mind dear, it\'92s just for a day or two.\'94 Susie closed her eyes.\
\
\'93Do you still want to call her Ellen?\'94\
\
The nurse brought back a basket and set it on the bed beside Susie.\
\
\'93Oh isn\'92t she wonderful!\'94 said Ed. \'93Look she\'92s breathing.... And\
they\'92ve oiled her.\'94 He helped his wife to raise herself on her elbow;\
the yellow coil of her hair unrolled, fell over his hand and arm. \'93How\
can you tell them apart nurse?\'94\
\
\'93Sometimes we cant,\'94 said the nurse, stretching her mouth in a smile.\
Susie was looking querulously into the minute purple face. \'93You\'92re sure\
this is mine.\'94\
\
\'93Of course.\'94\
\
\'93But it hasnt any label on it.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll label it right away.\'94\
\
\'93But mine was dark.\'94 Susie lay back on the pillow, gasping for breath.\
\
\'93She has lovely little light fuzz just the color of your hair.\'94\
\
Susie stretched her arms out above her head and shrieked: \'93It\'92s not\
mine. It\'92s not mine. Take it away.... That woman\'92s stolen my baby.\'94\
\
\'93Dear, for Heaven\'92s sake! Dear, for Heaven\'92s sake!\'94 He tried to tuck\
the covers about her.\
\
\'93Too bad,\'94 said the nurse, calmly, picking up the basket. \'93I\'92ll have to\
