front of the long windows smoking a pipe. Through the sliding doors\
into the front came a sound of glasses tinkling and shuffling feet and\
laughing and _Running Wild_ grating hazily out of a blunt needle on the\
phonograph.\
\
\'93Why dont you park here for the night?\'94 Hildebrand was saying in his\
deep serious voice. \'93Those people\'92ll fade out gradually.... We can put\
you up on the couch.\'94\
\
\'93No thanks,\'94 said Jimmy. \'93They\'92ll start talking psychoanalysis in a\
minute and they\'92ll be here till dawn.\'94\
\
\'93But you\'92d much better take a morning train.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not going to take any kind of a train.\'94\
\
\'93Say Herf did you read about the man in Philadelphia who was killed\
because he wore his straw hat on the fourteenth of May?\'94\
\
\'93By God if I was starting a new religion he\'92d be made a saint.\'94\
\
\'93Didnt you read about it? It was funny as a crutch.... This man had the\
temerity to defend his straw hat. Somebody had busted it and he started\
to fight, and in the middle of it one of these streetcorner heroes came\
up behind him and brained him with a piece of lead pipe. They picked\
him up with a cracked skull and he died in the hospital.\'94\
\
\'93Bob what was his name?\'94\
\
\'93I didnt notice.\'94\
\
\'93Talk about the Unknown Soldier.... That\'92s a real hero for you; the\
golden legend of the man who would wear a straw hat out of season.\'94\
\
A head was stuck between the double doors. A flushfaced man with his\
hair over his eyes looked in. \'93Cant I bring you fellers a shot of\
gin.... Whose funeral is being celebrated anyway?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m going to bed, no gin for me,\'94 said Hildebrand grouchily.\
\
\'93It\'92s the funeral of Saint Aloysius of Philadelphia, virgin and martyr,\
